summary: Pokemon Card of the Day #1305: Manectric (Arceus #22)
title: Pokemon Card of the Day #1305: Manectric (Arceus #22)
body:
Manectric was a Pokemon that really lacked damage output. The attacks looked like they belonged in a game from 2002, not 2009. Why even cover a card like this? Well, it did have an attack that did more damage to a Pokemon that had already taken damage, so there was potential for at least some sort of snowball effect here.

90 HP was standard on a Stage 1. and the +20 Fighting Weakness could occasionally make a difference if a Fighting-type had support from something like Crobat G. There was a -20 Metal Resistance here, which was better than nothing, though Metal was not a particularly good type at the time. The best thing in the stats was that Manectric could retreat for free, letting it try to pivot.

Second Bite started off poorly. 20 damage for 2 Energy was a joke. Luckily, 10 more was added for each damage counter on the Defending Pokemon, so it got better. The obvious goal here was to let some other Pokemon spread a ton of damage so Manectric could clean up later in a game. The problem here was that trying to find partners that could spread damage efficiently and work with a Lightning-type like Manectric was extremely hard, especially since there were a bunch of fast decks that would take advantage of the slower pace early on.

Swift was awful. 50 damage for 3 Energy that didn’t pay attention to Weakness, Resistance, or any other effects on the Defending Pokemon? Count me out.

Manectric had one intriguing attack in Second Bite, but it was so hard to use reliably that it didn’t find a place in any serious deck. It wasn’t even worth use casually, just because the Pokemon available didn’t really give the support it really needed. This would have been a cool card in 2005, but it just didn’t cut it in 2009-2010.
